Title: Quantify the Extent of Evolutionary Evidence in Molecular Sequences
Description: Biological inferences obtained from molecular data are only as
    good as the extent of evolutionary signatures retained in the genetic
    data. Techniques available to quantify these signatures are largely
    targeted towards phylogeny reconstruction and they often rely on adhoc
    hypothesis tests of significance. Here I present primarily Bayesian
    functions for assess whether a set of protein sequences are saturated.
    That is, to determine whether the evolutionary information in the
    sequences has eroded with time. Site specific Bayes factors are
    generated with respect to DNA, codon and amino acids to allow for
    straightforward applications in extensive computational biology
    inquiries, including natural selection analyses.
